{"title_page": "Mattie Moss Clark", "text_new": "{{moresources|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n|image =\n|image_size =\n|alias = Dr. Mattie Moss Clark\n|name  = Mattie Moss Clark\n|background = solo_singer\n|birth_name = Mattie Juliet Moss\n|birth_date = {{birth date|1925|3|26}}\n|birth_place = [[Selma, Alabama|Selma]], Alabama, United States\n|death_date = {{death date and age|1994|9|22|1925|3|26}}\n|death_place = [[Southfield, Michigan|Southfield]], Michigan, United States\n|occupation = {{flatlist|\n*Singer\n*songwriter\n*musician\n*record producer\n*manager\n*[[choir director]]\n}}\n|instruments = {{flatlist|\n*Vocals\n*piano\n*keyboards\n}}\n|alma mater = [[Selma University]]\n|years_active = 1958&ndash;1994\n|associated_acts = [[The Clark Sisters]]\n|label = {{flatlist|\n*[[Capitol Records|Capitol Christian Music Group]]\n*[[Sound of Gospel]]\n*[[Westbound Records|Westbound]]\n*[[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n*Rejoice\n*Sparrow\n}}\n|genre = {{flatlist|\n*[[gospel music|Gospel]]\n*[[urban contemporary gospel]]\n*[[Christian R&B]]\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Dr. Mattie Moss Clark''' (born '''Mattie Juliet Moss'''; March 26, 1925 \u2013 September 22, 1994) was an American [[gospel music|gospel]] choir director and the mother of [[The Clark Sisters]], a world-renowned gospel vocal group. Clark is credited for creating the three-part harmony (separating vocal parts into [[soprano]], [[alto (voice)|alto]] and [[tenor]]), a technique which is prevalent among gospel choirs today.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/6802026|title=Dr Mattie Juliet Moss Clark|publisher=Findagrave.com|accessdate=2012-03-06}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMattie Juliet Moss was born the seventh of nine children to ministers Fred John Moss and Mattie Juliet Walker in [[Selma, Alabama]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cogic.org/imd/2016/11/26/dr-mattie-moss-clark |title=Bio|website=www.cogic.org}}</ref >She began playing piano at six. By twelve, she had become the musician for her mother's services at the Holiness Temple Church of Christ in Prayer<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=xwZlDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT182&ots=nWIi4WdOd2&dq=Mattie%20Moss%20Clark%20Holiness%20Temple%20Church%20of%20Christ%20in%20Prayer&pg=PT182#v=onepage&q=Mattie%20Moss%20Clark%20Holiness%20Temple%20Church%20of%20Christ%20in%20Prayer&f=false|title=The Dictionary of Pan-African Pentecostalism, Volume One: North America|last=Alexander|first=Estrelda Y.|date=2018-06-22|publisher=Wipf and Stock Publishers|isbn=978-1-5326-6133-4|language=en}}</ref> and traveled with her mother to play at mission services, a trend she passed on to daughter [[Twinkie Clark|Twinkie]].<ref>http://www.ladydorindaclarkcole.net/mattie.html</ref>\n\nAfter high school, she attended [[Selma University]] and received training in classical music and choral singing. Moss moved to Detroit in her early twenties to be with her sister, Sybil Burke, and became a member of Greater Love Tabernacle Church of God in Christ. It was there that she received the gift of the Holy Ghost, and became Minister of Music.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1958, she recorded \"Going to Heaven to Meet the King\", with the Southwest Michigan State Choir, becoming the first person to commit the sounds of a choir to record. She was also the first person to separate vocal parts into soprano, alto and tenor. <ref>https://www.detroitnews.com/story/entertainment/2020/04/09/detroits-clark-sisters-finally-get-story-told-lifetime-film/5121066002/</ref> She received three gold albums with the Southwest Michigan State Choir, and went on to write and arrange hundreds of songs and recorded over 50 albums. She directed Cadillac Motor Company's Christmas choir for 11 years and also conducted community-wide mass choirs for the prestigious NAACP Freedom Fund Dinners.\n\nIn 1968, Clark and Elma Hendricks convened a Sing-A-Rama in Detroit at Reverend [[C. L. Franklin]]\u2018s [[New Bethel Baptist Church (Detroit, Michigan)]]. They formed a 1,000 voice choir and had legendary gospel singer, Reverend [[James Cleveland]] come in as a special guest. \u00a0Cleveland so enjoyed the music and teaching classes that he told Clark he would like to create a similar convocation and maybe call it the Music Workshop of America. \u00a0Clark suggested that he add \u201cGospel\u201d to the title to let prospective attendees know it was gospel music only. \u00a0Cleveland wasted no time in putting the word out. \u00a0The first [[Gospel Music Workshop of America]] (GMWA)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://praisedc.com/1352932/black-history-inspiration-spotlight-rev-james-cleveland/|title=Black History Inspiration Spotlight: Rev. James Cleveland|date=2013-02-02|website=Praise 104.1|language=en|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> convention took place in August 1968 at the King Solomon Baptist Church in Detroit. \u00a0The idea was to perpetuate the legacy and appreciation of gospel music through classes and provide an opportunity to expose new talent.\n\nIn 1979, she founded the Clark Conservatory of Music in Detroit, which established itself as one of the most prestigious schools of its kind in the country. In 1981, Trinity College in [[Pennsylvania]] conferred upon her one of their highest honors, the degree of Doctor of Humanities. After the death of Bishop Bailey in 1985, she continued as State Minister of Music for Southwest Michigan Jurisdiction #1, attending Greater Mitchell Church of God in Christ, under Bishop J.H. Sheard. <ref>https://www.malaco.com/artists/gospel/dr-mattie-moss-clark/</ref>\n\nShe was an editor and contributor to the hymnal published by the Church of God in Christ entitled, ''Yes, Lord.'' When the late Bishop J.O. Patterson appointed her the International President of the Music Department in 1968, she worked to instill within musicians and choirs a responsibility to Christ as well as capability for Christ. Throughout her efforts, young people especially received her and many were saved, filled with the Holy Ghost, and uplifted by her music and message.\n\nShe completely revolutionized the music departments. She gave definition to the role of State Minister of Music, traveled year-round to every state in the country conducting workshops, rehearsals and musicals to prepare choirs for service on the National Church level and organized the structure of the National Music Convention of the Church of God in Christ. \n\nDr. Clark introduced the workshop and seminar concept to the convention, and, along with her staff, structured classes for the convention and created \"A Song Is Born\", the program where new talent was introduced before thousands.\n\n==Personal life==\nClark married twice. By her first husband, whom she married on December 30, 1945, Leo Henry Cullum Sr., Clark mothered two children, Leo Henry Cullum, Jr. and [[Jacky Cullum Chisholm|Jacqueline Lenita \"Jacky\"]]. After their divorce, she married Elder Elbert Clark (1927-2001) on November 30, 1952 and had four children, Denise Darchell, [[Twinkie Clark|Elbernita]], [[Dorinda Clark Cole|Dorinda Grace]], and [[Karen Clark Sheard|Karen Valencia]]. The Clarks divorced in 1973. Dr. Clark mentored her daughters, having them sing as part of her and their father's church's choir. <ref>https://www.thecinemaholic.com/the-clark-sisters-first-ladies-of-gospel-true-story/</ref>\n\nIn 1973, shortly after divorcing Elbert Clark, Clark sparked the forming of [[The Clark Sisters]]. After nearly ten years, Clark passed all responsibility of the group to daughter Twinkie, who became the leader of the group. <ref>https://www.kennedy-center.org/artists/l/la-ln/the-legendary-clark-sisters/</ref> Though she became less active in her daughters' career, she remained frequently supportive, even attending and performing with her daughters at the [[25th Grammy Awards|1983 Grammy Awards]].\n\n==Later years==\nClark's health was starting to decline due to diabetes. Told by [[Dorinda Clark-Cole]], she had her right leg amputated and suffered a stroke which left her confined to a wheelchair. Despite failing health, Clark continued to record music into the last year of her life before succumbing to complications from diabetes on September 22, 1994 at Providence Hospital in [[Southfield]], Michigan, at age 69.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=xwZlDwAAQBAJ&lpg=PT182&ots=nWIi4WdOd2&dq=Mattie%20Moss%20Clark%20Holiness%20Temple%20Church%20of%20Christ%20in%20Prayer&pg=PT182#v=onepage&q=Mattie%20Moss%20Clark%20Holiness%20Temple%20Church%20of%20Christ%20in%20Prayer&f=false|title=The Dictionary of Pan-African Pentecostalism, Volume One: North America|last=Alexander|first=Estrelda Y.|date=2018-06-22|publisher=Wipf and Stock Publishers|isbn=978-1-5326-6133-4|language=en}}</ref> \n\nDr. Mattie Moss Clark\u2019s funeral was held on September 28, 1994 at Bailey Cathedral Church of God In Christ in Detroit, Michigan. Many renowned artist such as, [[Rance Allen]], [[Vanessa Bell Armstrong]], [[James Moore (singer)|James Moore]], and [[Aretha Franklin]] paid tribute to Clark with musical selections. \n\nShe was interred at Roseland Park Cemetery in [[Oakland County, Michigan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/30875075/dr_mattie_moss_clark_obituary/|title=Dr. Mattie Moss Clark Obituary|date=1994-09-24|work=Detroit Free Press|access-date=2020-02-04|pages=2}}</ref> \n\nActress [[Aunjanue Ellis]] played Clark in the 2020 Lifetime biopic ''[[The Clark Sisters: First Ladies of Gospel]]''. <ref>https://www.blackfilm.com/read/2020/03/clips-cast-photos-to-lifetimes-the-clark-sisters-the-first-ladies-of-gospel/</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===State Choir of Southwestern Michigan C.O.G.I.C. Albums===\n* ''Going To Heaven to Meet the King'' (1958)\n* ''Lord Do Something For Me'' (KAPP, 1959 KL-1258) - '''( Eugene J. Potts, Director)'''\n\n===Southwest Michigan State Choir Albums (Mattie Moss Clark, Composer, Arranger, Director and Co-Chairman)===\n* ''Lord Do Something For Me''                        '''(Kapp,  1958