{"title_page": "Fistral Bay Hotel", "text_new": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020|for=Needs detailed copy-edit for grammar and prose. }}\n\n{{Company\n| name                = NEX ZQUARE\n| logo                = nex zquare logo wi.png\n| founder             = CIBBUMON LS\n| NEX ZQUARE          = \n| CEO                 = CIBBUMON\n}}\n\n[[File:North-Northwest from the Fistral Bay Hotel - geograph.org.uk - 170164.jpg|thumb|234x234px|View From room 205.]]\n'''Fistral Bay Hotel''' is located in [[Newquay]], [[Cornwall]], England, United Kingdom. It was opened in 1931 and is built in a prominent position overlooking [[Fistral Beach]] and The Golf Links. \n\nAlthough the hotel was considered speculative, risky and unwelcome from the residents at the time, the hotels eventually reduced the negative impact on the harbour economy.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cornwalllive.com/news/inside-eerie-derelict-newquay-hotel-955407 |title=Inside the eerie hotel that has stood derelict for more than a decade|last=Smallcombe|first=Mike|date=2017-12-30|website=cornwalllive|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref>\n\nThe hotel has 60 rooms.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe hotel closed in 2006 after 75 years of business. It thrived during the 1950s and 1960s, as Newquay became a beneficiary of the diversion of domestic holiday demand to Cornwall and Devon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cornwalllive.com/news/cornwall-news/popular-cornwall-hotels-closed-2000s-2590671|title=The popular hotels of Cornwall lost over the past two decades|last=Becquart|first=Charlotte|date=2019-03-03|website=cornwalllive|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> As of December 2019, a businessman plans to purchase the former Fistral Bay Hotel as part of proposal to renovate and reopen the building as a hotel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newquayvoice.co.uk |title=A bid to Restore Hotel to former Glory|last=Wilkins|first=Warren|date=December 2019|work=The Newquay Voice}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Fistral Bay Hotel official opened in the Easter of 1931.\n\nDuring the early 1930's accommodation for visitors in Newquay was increasing as the town started to become busy as a tourist destination. Many hotels were expanding during this time such as the [[Great Western Hotel (Newquay)|Great Western Hotel]] and the Former St Brannocks Hotel.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|title=Newquay Hotels|date=9 April 1931|work=The Newquay Express|access-date=|url-status=live|year=1931}}</ref> Thus, the art-deco themed, Fistral Bay Hotel and The Pentire Hotel became the first purpose built hotels in Pentire, both with their unique designs.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe Hotel is mentioned in an Autobiography Called \"Just Me\" by [[Joan Ball]]. She described having to stay in [[Newquay]] for a short while during [[World War II|World War 2]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DSqdBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA13&dq=%22Fistral+Bay+Hotel%22+-wikipedia#v=onepage&q=%22Fistral%20Bay%20Hotel%22%20-wikipedia&f=false|title=Just Me by Joan Ball|last=Joan|first=Ball|date=2012|website=Google Ebooks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|isbn=9781312560147}}</ref>\n\n=== Hotel Fire ===\nOn the fifth of May, 1957, normal plans to open the hotel during the summer were delayed when a fire broke out. The fire was discovered when someone from the neighboring Phelima hotel saw flames spewing out from the foyer. Seconds later, windows cracked and smoke poured out. The Fire Brigade soon came, entering the building through the windows. They soon found the seat of the fire, underneath one of the main staircases; which had been enveloped in the fire. The fire was soon extinguished, however, this incident only having lasted three hours.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Hotel Fire At Newquay|date=May 1957|work=The Newquay Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe proprietress of the hotel Mrs M. E Lewes was not available when a Cornish guardian reporter called, but workmen were at the hotel the next day repairing the damage. It is understood that parties of New Zealand and Austrians visitors were expected that week.[[File:The Fistral Bay Hotel - Dance Floor.jpg|thumb|Fistral Bay Hotel Dance floor 2000]]\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n\n{{coord missing|Cornwall}}\n\n[[Category:Hotels in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Newquay]]\n[[Category:Hotels established in 1931]]\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 1931]]\n[[Category:1931 establishments in England]]\n__INDEX__\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|date=April 2020|for=Needs detailed copy-edit for grammar and prose. }}\n\n{{Infobox hotel\n| name = Fistral Bay Hotel\n| former_names = The Fistral Bay Hotel\n| image = Fistral Bay Hotel.jpg\n| status = Closed\n| address = 1 Pentire Ave, Newquay TR7 1NZ\n| location = Newquay, Cornwall,UK\n| caption = \n| opened_date = March 1931\n| floor_count = 4\n| architectural_style = Art-Deco\n| renovation_date = TBD\n| rooms = 60\n| website = www.fistralbayhotel.co.uk\n| map_caption = \n| ren_cost = 10 Million (Approximately)\n| architect = John Sansom\n}}\n\n[[File:North-Northwest from the Fistral Bay Hotel - geograph.org.uk - 170164.jpg|thumb|234x234px|View From room 205.]]\n'''Fistral Bay Hotel''' is located in [[Newquay]], [[Cornwall]], England, United Kingdom. It was opened in 1931 and is built in a prominent position overlooking [[Fistral Beach]] and The Golf Links. \n\nAlthough the hotel was considered speculative, risky and unwelcome from the residents at the time, the hotels eventually reduced the negative impact on the harbour economy.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cornwalllive.com/news/inside-eerie-derelict-newquay-hotel-955407 |title=Inside the eerie hotel that has stood derelict for more than a decade|last=Smallcombe|first=Mike|date=2017-12-30|website=cornwalllive|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref>\n\nThe hotel has 60 rooms.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe hotel closed in 2006 after 75 years of business. It thrived during the 1950s and 1960s, as Newquay became a beneficiary of the diversion of domestic holiday demand to Cornwall and Devon.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cornwalllive.com/news/cornwall-news/popular-cornwall-hotels-closed-2000s-2590671|title=The popular hotels of Cornwall lost over the past two decades|last=Becquart|first=Charlotte|date=2019-03-03|website=cornwalllive|access-date=2020-01-13}}</ref> As of December 2019, a businessman plans to purchase the former Fistral Bay Hotel as part of proposal to renovate and reopen the building as a hotel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.newquayvoice.co.uk |title=A bid to Restore Hotel to former Glory|last=Wilkins|first=Warren|date=December 2019|work=The Newquay Voice}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe Fistral Bay Hotel official opened in the Easter of 1931.\n\nDuring the early 1930's accommodation for visitors in Newquay was increasing as the town started to become busy as a tourist destination. Many hotels were expanding during this time such as the [[Great Western Hotel (Newquay)|Great Western Hotel]] and the Former St Brannocks Hotel.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|title=Newquay Hotels|date=9 April 1931|work=The Newquay Express|access-date=|url-status=live|year=1931}}</ref> Thus, the art-deco themed, Fistral Bay Hotel and The Pentire Hotel became the first purpose built hotels in Pentire, both with their unique designs.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe Hotel is mentioned in an Autobiography Called \"Just Me\" by [[Joan Ball]]. She described having to stay in [[Newquay]] for a short while during [[World War II|World War 2]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=DSqdBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA13&dq=%22Fistral+Bay+Hotel%22+-wikipedia#v=onepage&q=%22Fistral%20Bay%20Hotel%22%20-wikipedia&f=false|title=Just Me by Joan Ball|last=Joan|first=Ball|date=2012|website=Google Ebooks|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|isbn=9781312560147}}</ref>\n\n=== Hotel Fire ===\nOn the fifth of May, 1957, normal plans to open the hotel during the summer were delayed when a fire broke out. The fire was discovered when someone from the neighboring Phelima hotel saw flames spewing out from the foyer. Seconds later, windows cracked and smoke poured out. The Fire Brigade soon came, entering the building through the windows. They soon found the seat of the fire, underneath one of the main staircases; which had been enveloped in the fire. The fire was soon extinguished, however, this incident only having lasted three hours.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=|title=Hotel Fire At Newquay|date=May 1957|work=The Newquay Express|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe proprietress of the hotel Mrs M. E Lewes was not available when a Cornish guardian reporter called, but workmen were at the hotel the next day repairing the damage. It is understood that parties of New Zealand and Austrians visitors were expected that week.[[File:The Fistral Bay Hotel - Dance Floor.jpg|thumb|Fistral Bay Hotel Dance floor 2000]]\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n\n{{coord missing|Cornwall}}\n\n[[Category:Hotels in Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Newquay]]\n[[Category:Hotels established in 1931]]\n[[Category:Hotel buildings completed in 1931]]\n[[Category:1931 establishments in England]]\n__INDEX__\n\n==External links==\n* {{commonscat-inline}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n", "name_user": "Nexzquare", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fistral_Bay_Hotel"}
